      First Republic
   =20
 =20

I mostly think of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. as a US government re=
gulator that provides a government backstop on bank deposits. If a bank fai=
ls, the government =E2=80=94=C2=A0the FDIC =E2=80=94=C2=A0will come in and =
take it over and pay out all depositors (up to $250,000 each) with governme=
nt money. This backstop is what makes bank deposits safe, what makes them=
=C2=A0money:=C2=A0An FDIC-insured bank account=C2=A0has no credit risk, bec=
ause it is backed by the US government=E2=80=99s ability to print dollars.=
=C2=A0
There is another way to think about it, though, which is that the FDIC is a=
 sort of mutual-aid program=C2=A0among banks. If a bank fails, the FDIC wil=
l take it over and pay out any insured deposits, but the money does not com=
e from a government printing press but=C2=A0from the FDIC=E2=80=99s own sep=
arate insurance fund. And  this insurance fund, in turn, comes from the ban=
ks: It =E2=80=9Cis funded mainly through quarterly assessments on insured b=
anks,=E2=80=9D with each US bank paying some money every quarter based on i=
ts size and the risk it poses to the financial system.
Both of these ways of thinking about the FDIC are correct. The insurance fu=
nd =E2=80=94=C2=A0the pool of money that the banks pay into, which was abou=
t $128 billion as of December 2022 =E2=80=94 takes the first loss; if the F=
DIC needs to pay out any money to depositors, it comes from the insurance f=
und, and if the fund gets depleted then the banks pay higher assessments to=
 top it up. But  the fund =E2=80=9Cis backed by the full faith and credit o=
f the United States government,=E2=80=9D and if it runs out of money then i=
nsured deposits will still get paid.=C2=A0
Roughly speaking, if some banks fail, the FDIC is a mutual-aid program, and=
 the other banks join in to bear the loss. But if there=E2=80=99s a full-bl=
own systemic banking crisis and lots=C2=A0of banks fail, the FDIC is a gove=
rnment guarantee, and taxpayers save the banks.
You can see the appeal of this split. Without the government backstop, bank=
 deposits would not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0be money; there=E2=80=99d still be some=
 nagging doubt about whether they were safe. (And, of course,=C2=A0uninsure=
d=C2=A0deposits are also supposed to be quite money-like, and there=C2=A0is=
=C2=A0a bit of doubt about them.) But without the banking industry bearing =
the first loss, this would look too much like a free subsidy to the banks: =
Why should banks make a profit when things are good and then get bailed out=
 by taxpayers when they lose money? Having them be bailed out=C2=A0by each =
other=C2=A0seems a bit more fair.
Now, even aside from the FDIC, there is a long history=C2=A0of good banks r=
escuing failed banks for the good of the system as a whole.   Bankers under=
stand very well that, for banking to work, people need to have confidence i=
n=C2=A0the banking system, and the way to maintain that confidence is to ma=
ke sure that banks do not disappear and take depositors=E2=80=99 money with=
 them. Sometimes bankers come to this realization on their own; J.P. Morgan=
 (the guy) famously propped up failing banks during the  Panic of 1907, bef=
ore the FDIC was created. Other times, the government cajoles good banks in=
to saving bad ones; JPMorgan (the bank) famously  bought Bear Stearns & Co.=
 (an investment bank not backed by the FDIC) during the financial crisis of=
 2008 with the government=E2=80=99s encouragement.
The argument for a good bank to bail out a bad one in these scenarios is pr=
etty straightforward: =E2=80=9CIf you let Bank X fail, that will erode conf=
idence in the system, and next depositors will start taking their money out=
 of=C2=A0your=C2=A0bank, so you will be better off bailing out Bank X now.=
=E2=80=9D The good bank will be better off even if it loses money on the de=
al: Losing some money to bail out the bad bank is the price it pays to shor=
e up confidence in the system, and confidence in the system is worth more t=
o it than the money it loses.
  [1]

The specific mechanics of the FDIC insurance fund create another argument: =
=E2=80=9CIf you let Bank X fail, that will cost the FDIC money, and the FDI=
C will just send you a bill for that money, so you might as well bail out B=
ank X yourself first.=E2=80=9D  CNBC=E2=80=99s Hugh Son reports on First Re=
public Bank:

Advisors to First Republic will attempt to cajole the big U.S. banks who=E2=
=80=99ve already propped it up into doing one more favor, CNBC has learned.=
=C2=A0
The pitch will go something like this, according to bankers with knowledge =
of the situation: Purchase bonds from First Republic at above-market rates =
for a total loss of a few billion dollars =E2=80=93 or face roughly $30 bil=
lion in Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. fees when First Republic fails. =E2=
=80=A6
If the First Republic advisors manage to convince big banks to purchase bon=
ds for more than they are worth =E2=80=94 to take the hit of investment los=
ses for the good of the banking system, as well as their own welfare =E2=80=
=94 then they are confident that other parties will step up to help the ban=
k recapitalize itself.
The advisors have already lined up potential purchasers of new First Republ=
ic stock in that scenario, according to the sources.

Right? The 2023 US regional banking mini-crisis is not, I think, a full-blo=
wn systemic banking crisis in which the biggest banks are at risk. It is mu=
ch more a crisis in which=C2=A0a few medium-sized banks fail, which means t=
hat the solution to the crisis is mutual aid by banks. The FDIC is traditio=
nally the=C2=A0intermediary=C2=A0for that aid, but there are different ways=
 for that to work. =E2=80=9CThe FDIC seizes the bank, sells its assets, pay=
s out deposits, loses money and assesses the other banks for the loss=E2=80=
=9D is the strict formal process in the law, but =E2=80=9Cthe FDIC gets the=
 other banks to fix the problem by threatening to use the formal process=E2=
=80=9D is more flexible and efficient.
Similarly, Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Gillian Tan and Matthew Monks   reported yes=
terday that First Republic is looking to sell up to $100 billion of assets,=
 and that =E2=80=9Cpotential buyers, including large US banks, could receiv=
e warrants or preferred equity as an incentive to buy assets above their ma=
rket value, one of the people said.=E2=80=9D You almost don=E2=80=99t need =
warrants or preferred equity: The goal is to get other banks to buy First R=
epublic=E2=80=99s assets (or its bonds, or=C2=A0whatever) at above their ma=
rket value, in order to take some of First Republic=E2=80=99s losses off of=
 its books and put them on the other banks=E2=80=99 books, and the incentiv=
e for the other banks to do that is that they are all in this together and =
if First Republic goes bust they=E2=80=99ll pay for it one way or another. =
Their finances are tied to First Republic=E2=80=99s, even without warrants.
First Republic=E2=80=99s   stock collapsed on this news. Part of the reason=
 is that, if First Republic really is going to sell stock in the near futur=
e, it will probably be at a pretty low price: If JPMorgan Chase & Co. is go=
ing to be bearing some of First Republic=E2=80=99s losses, it=E2=80=99s a s=
afe bet that so will First Republic=E2=80=99s shareholders.
But part of the reason is that this news suggests First Republic=C2=A0will=
=C2=A0sell stock, or at least do=C2=A0something, in the near future. I   wr=
ote yesterday that there is nothing in principle really stopping First Repu=
blic from being a zombie bank indefinitely: It can fund itself with loans f=
rom the Federal Reserve and friendly supportive deposits from big banks, an=
d while that funding is expensive and it will not be particularly profitabl=
e, it can keep going for a while and maybe things will improve. But that do=
es depend on the good will of the FDIC and the Fed (and the big banks), and=
 on their confidence that First Republic is solvent. And that confidence ma=
y be fading; Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Katanga Johnson reports:

US bank regulators are weighing the prospect of downgrading their private a=
ssessments of First Republic Bank =E2=80=94 a move that may curb the troubl=
ed firm=E2=80=99s access to Federal Reserve lending facilities.
The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has been giving the bank time to reach =
a private deal to shore up its finances. But as weeks keep passing without =
a transaction, senior officials are increasingly weighing whether to downgr=
ade their scoring of the firm=E2=80=99s condition, including its so-called =
Camels rating, according to people with direct knowledge of the talks. That=
 would likely limit the bank=E2=80=99s use of the Fed=E2=80=99s discount wi=
ndow and an emergency facility launched last month, the people said.

Meanwhile, I argued, it=E2=80=99s quite hard for First Republic to find a=
=C2=A0buyer, or even to raise capital, because its assets probably are wort=
h less than its liabilities. In that scenario, it would make a kind of sens=
e for First Republic to just zombie along: Actually fixing the problem woul=
d require First Republic (and the FDIC, and the other banks) to recognize l=
osses, while doing nothing can defer them. The fact that First Republic=E2=
=80=99s advisers are pushing to recognize and share the losses suggests tha=
t the FDIC is pushing them to take the losses, which suggests that time is =
running out.

