      Getty=C2=A0
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about a guy, Scott Murray, who put out a press releas=
e saying that his firm, Trillium Capital LLC,=C2=A0would buy Getty Images H=
oldings Inc. for $4 billion, conditional on finding someone to give him $4 =
billion. This is, I should say, a condition that sometimes exists in merger=
 proposals. Last year Elon Musk announced that he would buy Twitter Inc. fo=
r $40=C2=A0billion if he could find $40=C2=A0billion, and people =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0certainly including me =E2=80=94=C2=A0expressed some doubt that he wo=
uld be able to raise the $40=C2=A0billion. And Twitter=E2=80=99s board of d=
irectors kind of held him off until he=C2=A0did=C2=A0find the money,   but =
he did, and then they really had no choice but to negotiate and ultimately=
=C2=A0sell to him.
Or, like, a big private equity sponsor might put in a proposal to buy a com=
pany, and the proposal will say something like =E2=80=9Cthis proposal is no=
t binding and is conditional on receiving customary financing.=E2=80=9D And=
 the company might very well reply =E2=80=9Cokay, sounds good, let=E2=80=99=
s talk,=E2=80=9D and the private equity firm will start due diligence and n=
egotiate a deal and talk to its bankers about raising the financing. And th=
en if, while they are negotiating, the leveraged finance market collapses, =
the private equity firm will say =E2=80=9Cah well never mind, can=E2=80=99t=
 get the money=E2=80=9D and the deal will die. The company knew that the pr=
oposal was contingent on financing, and knowingly took the risk that it mig=
ht be wasting its time, because it figured the financing would=C2=A0probabl=
y come through and it probably wouldn=E2=80=99t be a waste.
But there are, you know, context clues. If somebody with $200 billion of pe=
rsonal wealth says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy your company if I can raise $4=
0 billion,=E2=80=9D that might be worth looking into. If a firm that has pr=
eviously done lots of multibillion-dollar buyouts with lots of borrowed mon=
ey says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy your company if I can borrow $4=C2=A0bill=
ion from my usual banks,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s worth looking into. If=C2=
=A0I=C2=A0put out a press release saying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy Twitter =
for $40 billion if somebody gives me $40=C2=A0billion,=E2=80=9D that could =
be a true statement =E2=80=94=C2=A0lots of people would buy lots of luxury =
objects if someone gave them the money to do so! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is n=
ot one that Twitter=E2=80=99s management should take very seriously, becaus=
e there is absolutely no reason to think that anyone would give me $40 bill=
ion.
Still there is some nuance here. In a traditional leveraged buyout, the buy=
er borrows most of the money to do the deal, and the lenders lend the money=
 not because they like the=C2=A0buyer=E2=80=99s=C2=A0credit but because the=
y like the=C2=A0company=E2=80=99s=C2=A0credit. It=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=9CI =
will buy your company for $4 billion if I can borrow $3 billion from a bank=
,=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9CI will buy your company for $4 billion if=C2=
=A0your company=C2=A0can borrow $3 billion from a bank.=E2=80=9D If the com=
pany=C2=A0can=C2=A0borrow $3 billion from the bank, anyone with $1 billion =
could credibly make that offer. Of course you need the $1 billion, but I su=
ppose you can syndicate the equity as well. Lots of big credible repeat-pla=
yer investors buy companies with relatively little of their own money, and =
I suppose anyone could =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, could=C2=A0try=C2=A0to copy tha=
t model?
Anyway  here=E2=80=99s Getty=E2=80=99s response to Murray:

Consistent with its fiduciary obligations, the Board of Getty Images will d=
raw upon its collective and extensive experience to engage with and evaluat=
e credible and constructive proposals if presented.
The Board of Getty Images acknowledges an unsolicited, non-binding and high=
ly conditioned proposal from Trillium Capital LLC to acquire an unstated vo=
lume of outstanding shares of Getty Images for $10.00 per share announced v=
ia press release on April 24, 2023.
Trillium Capital LLC has not provided the Board of Getty Images or its advi=
sors with any evidence that it, its managing partner or its non-binding, hi=
ghly conditional proposal are sufficiently credible to warrant engagement b=
y the Board of Getty Images.
Absent further details and the demonstration of credibility by Trillium Cap=
ital LLC, the Board of Getty Images believes the current management team an=
d company strategy represent the best path forward to maximize the long-ter=
m shareholder value.

The problem for Murray is that he absolutely cannot raise the $4 billion he=
 needs to buy Getty unless Getty is willing to talk to him, and Getty is no=
t willing to talk to him unless he can credibly promise to raise the $4 bil=
lion. Ah well.
The stock is up a bit today? It closed at $5.06 per share on Friday, before=
 Murray=E2=80=99s $10-per-share offer, and at $6.63 on Monday, after climbi=
ng as high as $8.18 when he announced the offer; it was trading at about $6=
.47=C2=A0at 1 p.m today. I suppose if Getty won=E2=80=99t talk to him he wi=
ll just have to sell his shares? At 27% above where the stock was trading=
=C2=A0before he put out this press release? Ah well.

