   =20
      Meanwhile in crypto
   =20
 =20

Celsius Network is one of several cryptocurrency shadow banks that attracte=
d customers by telling them that the traditional financial system was bad a=
nd rigged against them and that they should trust Celsius instead. =E2=80=
=9CEither the bank is lying or Celsius is lying,=E2=80=9D founder Alex Mash=
insky said, correctly. Celsius is now extravagantly bankrupt=C2=A0and its c=
ustomers are having limited luck getting their money back. If you are a cus=
tomer who was attracted to Celsius by the pitch that the traditional system=
 is bad and rigged, and only crypto is trustworthy, what do you make of thi=
s? I suppose the two possibilities are:
=09=E2=80=9COops, I was wrong, turns out there is some value in regulation =
and disclosure and deposit insurance=E2=80=9D; or=09Double down: The tradit=
ional system is rigged, crypto is the future, do your own research,=C2=A0et=
c.

Yeah I mean obviously it=E2=80=99s No. 2. At Bloomberg Businessweek,   Stev=
en Church and Amelia Pollard check in on the crypto shadow bank bankruptcie=
s:

A certain breed of retail investors piled their money into crypto for its a=
nti-establishment qualities. Avoiding big banks or hidebound regulators swe=
etened the taste of uncanny returns. Crypto firms stoked that sentiment, pu=
lling in investor money by promising a world of =E2=80=9Cunparalleled econo=
mic freedom,=E2=80=9D as Celsius Network put it, or to make =E2=80=9Ccrypto=
 for all=E2=80=9D a reality, in the words of Voyager Digital.
But now millions of crypto fans=E2=80=94and their money=E2=80=94find themse=
lves trapped in a different kind of reality. Companies they trusted with th=
eir cryptocurrency have failed, and their assets are stuck in bankruptcy co=
urt, one of the most establishment and bureaucratic institutions in America=
. How much money the investors lose will be set by judges enforcing complex=
 rules written long before the first crypto coin was minted.
The process has already led to angry clashes on Zoom, where bankruptcy cour=
t hearings moved during the pandemic. Alah Shehadeh, who invested $80,000 o=
n the Voyager platform, was thrown out of a key hearing in March after repe=
atedly interrupting the judge, lawyers and witnesses. At one point he shout=
ed, =E2=80=9CYou are a terrible judge. You are robbing us. This is a crime.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
Some customers of the failed crypto platforms have taken the bankruptcy leg=
alese as a challenge, spending dozens of hours a week wading through filing=
s and hearings. One Telegram chat group has more than two dozen creditors w=
ho regularly communicate with one another. Immanuel Herrmann, an active cre=
ditor who=E2=80=99s represented himself in court, organized more than 500 c=
reditors to sign a letter opposing a motion to give Celsius more time to fi=
le a reorganization plan. =E2=80=9CThey understand crypto better than anyon=
e,=E2=80=9D says David Adler, a lawyer who represents a group of creditors =
in the Celsius case. =E2=80=9CBut the problem is translating that into the =
legal principles that the court has to apply.=E2=80=9D

I insist that if you put your money in Celsius then you did not =E2=80=9Cun=
derstand crypto better than anyone=E2=80=9D! The very most important thing =
to understand in finance and economics is that when a person says =E2=80=9C=
either the bank is lying or I am lying,=E2=80=9D you must not give him your=
 money! If you spend your time learning cryptography and working through bl=
ockchain consensus mechanisms and comparing yields of different DeFi projec=
ts, and then some guy is like =E2=80=9Chand over your money to me and I pro=
mise I=E2=80=99ll give it back with 18% interest, no risk, economic freedom=
!=E2=80=9D and you believe him, then you wasted your time understanding all=
 the other stuff. All financial complexity is a footnote to =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=
=80=99t hand all your money to some random guy promising high returns.=E2=
=80=9D
Though it will save you time=C2=A0now=C2=A0to understand that if you handed=
 him your money and he lost iit and went bankrupt, the bankruptcy court is =
not going to=C2=A0magically give you back your money.=C2=A0The money is gon=
e! The judge doesn=E2=80=99t have it! It=E2=80=99s not the judge=E2=80=99s =
fault! What you have is a bankruptcy claim! That=E2=80=99s what happens whe=
n you trust random guys with your money! They lose it!=C2=A0
Elsewhere in   crypto shadow bank bankruptcies:

Binance.US terminated an agreement to purchase the bankrupt crypto broker V=
oyager Digital Holdings Ltd., less than a week after federal regulators dro=
pped their efforts to halt the deal in court.
The decision came after months of wrangling and the intervention of multipl=
e federal and state regulators over the deal. In a statement, Binance.US sa=
id =E2=80=9Cthe hostile and uncertain regulatory climate in the United Stat=
es has introduced an unpredictable operating environment impacting the enti=
re American business community.=E2=80=9D

Yes, look, if I were a highly profitable international crypto exchange  in =
the crosshairs of US regulators, I would not want to add to my US business =
either. Obviously the better time for US regulators to crack down on crypto=
 would have been=C2=A0before=C2=A0Voyager went bankrupt and lost its custom=
ers=E2=80=99 money, and it=E2=80=99s inconvenient for those customers that =
the current US crackdown has prevented them from getting their money back (=
from Binance). But I suppose the regulatory goal is to make it as hard as p=
ossible for anyone=C2=A0else=C2=A0in the US to trust their money to a bankr=
upt crypto platform.

