0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">First Republic</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mostly think of the Federal Deposit Insuranc=
e Corp. as a US government regulator that provides a government backstop on=
 bank deposits. If a bank fails, the government =E2=80=94=C2=A0the FDIC =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0will come in and take it over and pay out all depositors (up to=
 $250,000 each) with government money. This backstop is what makes bank dep=
osits safe, what makes them=C2=A0<em>money:=C2=A0</em>An FDIC-insured bank =
account=C2=A0<em>has no credit risk</em>, because it is backed by the US go=
vernment=E2=80=99s ability to print dollars.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is another way to think about it, though=
, which is that the FDIC is a sort of mutual-aid program=C2=A0<em>among ban=
ks</em>. If a bank fails, the FDIC will take it over and pay out any insure=
d deposits, but the money does not come from a government printing press bu=
t=C2=A0from the FDIC=E2=80=99s own separate insurance fund. And <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuZmRpYy5nb3YvcmVzb3VyY2VzL2RlcG9zaXQtaW5zdXJhbmNlL2RlcG9zaXQtaW5zdXJhbmNl=
LWZ1bmQv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdfa609dd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this insurance fund</a=
>, in turn, comes from the banks: It =E2=80=9Cis funded mainly through quar=
terly assessments on insured banks,=E2=80=9D with each US bank paying some =
money every quarter based on its size and the risk it poses to the financia=
l system.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both of these ways of thinking about the FDIC =
are correct. The insurance fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0the pool of money that the b=
anks pay into, which was about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmRpYy5nb3YvYW5hbHlzaXMvcXVhcn=
Rlcmx5LWJhbmtpbmctcHJvZmlsZS9xYnAvMjAyMmRlYy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4b1d=
fe80" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">$128 billion</a> as of December 2022 =E2=80=94 takes the firs=
t loss; if the FDIC needs to pay out any money to depositors, it comes from=
 the insurance fund, and if the fund gets depleted then the banks pay highe=
r assessments to top it up. But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmRpYy5nb3YvcmVzb3VyY2VzL2Rlc=
G9zaXQtaW5zdXJhbmNlL2RlcG9zaXQtaW5zdXJhbmNlLWZ1bmQv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cCdfa609dd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> the fund</a> =E2=80=9Cis backed by the full faith and =
credit of the United States government,=E2=80=9D and if it runs out of mone=
y then insured deposits will still get paid.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Roughly speaking, if <em>some </em>banks fail,=
 the FDIC is a mutual-aid program, and the other banks join in to bear the =
loss. But if there=E2=80=99s a full-blown systemic banking crisis and <em>l=
ots=C2=A0</em>of banks fail, the FDIC is a government guarantee, and taxpay=
ers save the banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can see the appeal of this split. Without =
the government backstop, bank deposits would not=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0</em>b=
e money; there=E2=80=99d still be some nagging doubt about whether they wer=
e safe. (And, of course,=C2=A0<em>uninsured=C2=A0</em>deposits are also sup=
posed to be quite money-like, and there=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>a bit of doub=
t about them.) But without the banking industry bearing the first loss, thi=
s would look too much like a free subsidy to the banks: Why should banks ma=
ke a profit when things are good and then get bailed out by taxpayers when =
they lose money? Having them be bailed out=C2=A0<em>by each other=C2=A0</em=
>seems a bit more fair.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, even aside from the FDIC, there is a long=
 history=C2=A0of good banks rescuing failed banks for the good of the syste=
m as a whole. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3129=
1800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjM=
tMDMtMTcvYmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJlcHVibGljLXdpdGgtdGhlaXItbW9uZXk_Y2=
1waWQ9QkJEMDQyNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld=
3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDI2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBa30c86d4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bankers understand very well</a> that, fo=
r banking to work, people need to have confidence in=C2=A0<em>the banking s=
ystem</em>, and the way to maintain that confidence is to make sure that ba=
nks do not disappear and take depositors=E2=80=99 money with them. Sometime=
s bankers come to this realization on their own; J.P. Morgan (the guy) famo=
usly propped up failing banks during the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dp=
a2kvUGFuaWNfb2ZfMTkwNw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB36cd013d" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Panic of=
 1907</a>, before the FDIC was created. Other times, the government cajoles=
 good banks into saving bad ones; JPMorgan (the bank) famously <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAxOC8wMy8xNC9hLWRlY2FkZS1hZnRlci1pdHMtZmlyZS1zYWxlLWRlYWwtZ=
m9yLWJlYXItYS1sb29rLWF0LXdoYXQtanAtbW9yZ2FuLWdvdC1pbi10aGUtYmFyZ2Fpbi5odG1s=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc65cadaa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> bought Bear Stearns &amp; Co.<=
/a> (an investment bank not backed by the FDIC) during the financial crisis=
 of 2008 with the government=E2=80=99s encouragement.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The argument for a good bank to bail out a bad=
 one in these scenarios is pretty straightforward: =E2=80=9CIf you let Bank=
 X fail, that will erode confidence in the system, and next depositors will=
 start taking their money out of=C2=A0<em>your=C2=A0</em>bank, so you will =
be better off bailing out Bank X now.=E2=80=9D The good bank will be better=
 off even if it loses money on the deal: Losing some money to bail out the =
bad bank is the price it pays to shore up confidence in the system, and con=
fidence in the system is worth more to it than the money it loses.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The specific mechanics of the FDIC insurance f=
und create another argument: =E2=80=9CIf you let Bank X fail, that will cos=
t the FDIC money, and the FDIC will just send you a bill for that money, so=
 you might as well bail out Bank X yourself first.=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
25iYy5jb20vMjAyMy8wNC8yNi9maXJzdC1yZXB1YmxpYy1yZXNjdWUtcGl0Y2gtaGVscC1ub3ct=
b3ItcGF5LW1vcmUtbGF0ZXItd2hlbi1pdC1mYWlscy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa=
c088dc6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> CNBC=E2=80=99s Hugh Son reports on First Republic Bank</a=
>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Advisors to First Republic will attempt to caj=
ole the big U.S. banks who=E2=80=99ve already propped it up into doing one =
more favor, CNBC has learned.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pitch will go something like this, accordi=
ng to bankers with knowledge of the situation: Purchase bonds from First Re=
public at above-market rates for a total loss of a few billion dollars =E2=
=80=93 or face roughly $30 billion in Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. fees =
when First Republic fails. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the First Republic advisors manage to convi=
nce big banks to purchase bonds for more than they are worth =E2=80=94 to t=
ake the hit of investment losses for the good of the banking system, as wel=
l as their own welfare =E2=80=94 then they are confident that other parties=
 will step up to help the bank recapitalize itself.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The advisors have already lined up potential p=
urchasers of new First Republic stock in that scenario, according to the so=
urces.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right? The 2023 US regional banking mini-crisi=
s is not, I think, a full-blown systemic banking crisis in which the bigges=
t banks are at risk. It is much more a crisis in which=C2=A0a few medium-si=
zed banks fail, which means that the solution to the crisis is mutual aid b=
y banks. The FDIC is traditionally the=C2=A0<em>intermediary=C2=A0</em>for =
that aid, but there are different ways for that to work. =E2=80=9CThe FDIC =
seizes the bank, sells its assets, pays out deposits, loses money and asses=
ses the other banks for the loss=E2=80=9D is the strict formal process in t=
he law, but =E2=80=9Cthe FDIC gets the other banks to fix the problem by th=
reatening to use the formal process=E2=80=9D is more flexible and efficient=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Gillian Tan and=
 Matthew Monks <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/312=
91800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMD=
QtMjUvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtc2FpZC10by13ZWlnaC11cC10by0xMDAtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi1hc=
3NldC1zYWxlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0=
bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA0MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R=
1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11e83d0c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  reported yesterday</a> th=
at First Republic is looking to sell up to $100 billion of assets, and that=
 =E2=80=9Cpotential buyers, including large US banks, could receive warrant=
s or preferred equity as an incentive to buy assets above their market valu=
e, one of the people said.=E2=80=9D You almost don=E2=80=99t need warrants =
or preferred equity: The goal is to get other banks to buy First Republic=
=E2=80=99s assets (or its bonds, or=C2=A0whatever) at above their market va=
lue, in order to take some of First Republic=E2=80=99s losses off of its bo=
oks and put them on the other banks=E2=80=99 books, and the incentive for t=
he other banks to do that is that they are all in this together and if Firs=
t Republic goes bust they=E2=80=99ll pay for it one way or another. Their f=
inances are tied to First Republic=E2=80=99s, even without warrants.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First Republic=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjYvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtc2hhcmVzLX=
NsaXAtb24tcmVwb3J0LW9mLWJ1eWVycy1mb3ItbmV3LXN0b2NrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MjYyM19NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTIzMDQyNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5831c68=
5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  stock collapsed</a> on this news. Part of the reason is that=
, if First Republic really is going to sell stock in the near future, it wi=
ll probably be at a pretty low price: If JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. is going =
to be bearing some of First Republic=E2=80=99s losses, it=E2=80=99s a safe =
bet that so will First Republic=E2=80=99s shareholders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But part of the reason is that this news sugge=
sts First Republic=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>sell stock, or at least do=C2=A0=
<em>something</em>, in the near future. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjUvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1jcm=
VkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLXMtZ3JlYXQtYXdmdWwtcXVhcnRlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI2MjNfTU9ORVlTV=
FVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA0=
MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc6542486" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  wrote yesterday</a> that there is nothing in principle really stoppin=
g First Republic from being a zombie bank indefinitely: It can fund itself =
with loans from the Federal Reserve and friendly supportive deposits from b=
ig banks, and while that funding is expensive and it will not be particular=
ly profitable, it can keep going for a while and maybe things will improve.=
 But that does depend on the good will of the FDIC and the Fed (and the big=
 banks), and on their confidence that First Republic is solvent. And that c=
onfidence may be fading; Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/31291800.264436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjYvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtc2FpZC10by1mYWNlLXB=
vdGVudGlhbC1jdXJiLW9uLWJvcnJvd2luZy1mcm9tLWZlZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI2MjNfTU9ORV=
lTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yM=
zA0MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9244a0c8" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">  Katanga Johnson reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US bank regulators are weighing the prospect o=
f downgrading their private assessments of First Republic Bank =E2=80=94 a =
move that may curb the troubled firm=E2=80=99s access to Federal Reserve le=
nding facilities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has been g=
iving the bank time to reach a private deal to shore up its finances. But a=
s weeks keep passing without a transaction, senior officials are increasing=
ly weighing whether to downgrade their scoring of the firm=E2=80=99s condit=
ion, including its so-called Camels rating, according to people with direct=
 knowledge of the talks. That would likely limit the bank=E2=80=99s use of =
the Fed=E2=80=99s discount window and an emergency facility launched last m=
onth, the people said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, I argued, it=E2=80=99s quite hard f=
or First Republic to find a=C2=A0<em>buyer</em>, or even to raise capital, =
because its assets probably are worth less than its liabilities. In that sc=
enario, it would make a kind of sense for First Republic to just zombie alo=
ng: Actually fixing the problem would require First Republic (and the FDIC,=
 and the other banks) to recognize losses, while doing nothing can defer th=
em. The fact that First Republic=E2=80=99s advisers are pushing to recogniz=
e and share the losses suggests that the FDIC is pushing them to take the l=
osses, which suggests that time is running out.</p>
