<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or, like, a big private equity sponsor might p=
ut in a proposal to buy a company, and the proposal will say something like=
 =E2=80=9Cthis proposal is not binding and is conditional on receiving cust=
omary financing.=E2=80=9D And the company might very well reply =E2=80=9Cok=
ay, sounds good, let=E2=80=99s talk,=E2=80=9D and the private equity firm w=
ill start due diligence and negotiate a deal and talk to its bankers about =
raising the financing. And then if, while they are negotiating, the leverag=
ed finance market collapses, the private equity firm will say =E2=80=9Cah w=
ell never mind, can=E2=80=99t get the money=E2=80=9D and the deal will die.=
 The company knew that the proposal was contingent on financing, and knowin=
gly took the risk that it might be wasting its time, because it figured the=
 financing would=C2=A0<em>probably </em>come through and it <em>probably</e=
m> wouldn=E2=80=99t be a waste.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are, you know, context clues. If som=
ebody with $200 billion of personal wealth says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy y=
our company if I can raise $40 billion,=E2=80=9D that might be worth lookin=
g into. If a firm that has previously done lots of multibillion-dollar buyo=
uts with lots of borrowed money says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy your company=
 if I can borrow $4=C2=A0billion from my usual banks,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=
=99s worth looking into. If=C2=A0<em>I=C2=A0</em>put out a press release sa=
ying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy Twitter for $40 billion if somebody gives me=
 $40=C2=A0billion,=E2=80=9D that could be a true statement =E2=80=94=C2=A0l=
ots of people would buy lots of luxury objects if someone gave them the mon=
ey to do so! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is not one that Twitter=E2=80=99s manage=
ment should take very seriously, because there is absolutely no reason to t=
hink that anyone would give me $40 billion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there is some nuance here. In a traditio=
nal leveraged buyout, the buyer borrows most of the money to do the deal, a=
nd the lenders lend the money not because they like the=C2=A0<em>buyer=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0</em>credit but because they like the=C2=A0<em>company=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0</em>credit. It=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=9CI will buy your company fo=
r $4 billion if I can borrow $3 billion from a bank,=E2=80=9D but rather =
=E2=80=9CI will buy your company for $4 billion if=C2=A0<em>your company=C2=
=A0</em>can borrow $3 billion from a bank.=E2=80=9D If the company=C2=A0<em=
>can=C2=A0</em>borrow $3 billion from the bank, anyone with $1 billion coul=
d credibly make that offer. Of course you need the $1 billion, but I suppos=
e you can syndicate the equity as well. Lots of big credible repeat-player =
investors buy companies with relatively little of their own money, and I su=
ppose anyone could =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, could=C2=A0<em>try=C2=A0</em>to cop=
y that model?</p>
