Pollard check in</a> on the crypto shadow bank bankruptcies:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A certain breed of retail investors piled thei=
r money into crypto for its anti-establishment qualities. Avoiding big bank=
s or hidebound regulators sweetened the taste of uncanny returns. Crypto fi=
rms stoked that sentiment, pulling in investor money by promising a world o=
f =E2=80=9Cunparalleled economic freedom,=E2=80=9D as Celsius Network put i=
t, or to make =E2=80=9Ccrypto for all=E2=80=9D a reality, in the words of V=
oyager Digital.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now millions of crypto fans=E2=80=94and th=
eir money=E2=80=94find themselves trapped in a different kind of reality. C=
ompanies they trusted with their cryptocurrency have failed, and their asse=
ts are stuck in bankruptcy court, one of the most establishment and bureauc=
ratic institutions in America. How much money the investors lose will be se=
t by judges enforcing complex rules written long before the first crypto co=
in was minted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The process has already led to angry clashes o=
n Zoom, where bankruptcy court hearings moved during the pandemic. Alah She=
hadeh, who invested $80,000 on the Voyager platform, was thrown out of a ke=
y hearing in March after repeatedly interrupting the judge, lawyers and wit=
nesses. At one point he shouted, =E2=80=9CYou are a terrible judge. You are=
 robbing us. This is a crime.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some customers of the failed crypto platforms =
have taken the bankruptcy legalese as a challenge, spending dozens of hours=
 a week wading through filings and hearings. One Telegram chat group has mo=
re than two dozen creditors who regularly communicate with one another. Imm=
anuel Herrmann, an active creditor who=E2=80=99s represented himself in cou=
rt, organized more than 500 creditors to sign a letter opposing a motion to=
 give Celsius more time to file a reorganization plan. =E2=80=9CThey unders=
tand crypto better than anyone,=E2=80=9D says David Adler, a lawyer who rep=
resents a group of creditors in the Celsius case. =E2=80=9CBut the problem =
is translating that into the legal principles that the court has to apply.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I insist that if you put your money in Celsius=
 then you did not =E2=80=9Cunderstand crypto better than anyone=E2=80=9D! T=
he very most important thing to understand in finance and economics is that=
 when a person says =E2=80=9Ceither the bank is lying or I am lying,=E2=80=
=9D you must not give him your money! If you spend your time learning crypt=
ography and working through blockchain consensus mechanisms and comparing y=
ields of different DeFi projects, and then some guy is like =E2=80=9Chand o=
ver your money to me and I promise I=E2=80=99ll give it back with 18% inter=
est, no risk, economic freedom!=E2=80=9D and you believe him, then you wast=
ed your time understanding all the other stuff. All financial complexity is=
 a footnote to =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t hand all your money to some random gu=
y promising high returns.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though it will save you time=C2=A0<em>now=C2=
=A0</em>to understand that if you handed him your money and he lost iit and=
 went bankrupt, the bankruptcy court is not going to=C2=A0<em>magically giv=
e you back your money.</em>=C2=A0The money is gone! The judge doesn=E2=80=
=99t have it! It=E2=80=99s not the judge=E2=80=99s fault! What you have is =
a bankruptcy claim! That=E2=80=99s what happens when you trust random guys =
with your money! They lose it!=C2=A0</p>
